*sigh* Okay class, settle down, let me teach you the sacred art of creating and editing in a no create domain.

Now, there are a few ways you can do this:
1. Use avatar entities. You get 42 of them (go figure) and unless otherwise limited by a filter, no one can do **** to them (even admins can't delete them)!
2. Use remote execution. This is more complicated so moving on.
3. Edit what already exists.

That last one is the easiest so let's pick a domain called.... domain. Now, in this domain, we have a single cube and luck be with us that it's unlocked. Unlocked entities can always be manipulated, unless otherwise specified by the domain's or zone's filter.

Now, can anyone tell me how one would normally edit an entity? Anyone? No?

Why, you use Entities.editEntities! All you need to know is the UUID, or the "universally unique identifier," of the object we want to change. I won't go into detail how one would acquire our demonstration's cube, but any scripter worth their salt can think of a few ways. So for now, let's say the UUID is {fecc}.

So let's go ahead and troll the owner by scaling the cube!

Entities.editEntities("{fecc}",{dimensions:{x:10,y:1,z:10});

And walla! Now we have a flat, 10x10 platform! And you can edit any property you desire with this. Position? Whirl it away! Collision? Make a virtual sandpit!

Now now, I can hear a few of you in the back crying out, "But how do we stop this?" Right! There are a few ways!

1. Lock your **** down, dumb***! Unless the user has lock permissions, they can't unlock it to edit it!
2. Use a filter! Filters can moderate what edits are performed, so you could do something like this:
```
function filter(properties, filterType, originalProperties) {
if (filterType === EDIT) {
var willWork = 
(properties.dimensions.x > 10) ||
(properties.dimensions.y > 10) || 
(properties.dimensions.z > 10);
return !willWork;
}
filter.wantsOriginalProperties = false;
filter.wantsToFilterEdit = true;
}```
This filter will prevent us from making any edits bigger than 10m in any direction! If we try to make it 20 x 5 x 5, it simply will not work!

Hand in the back, yes? "But how do we stop people from making avatar entities?" Good question, and High Fidelity seems to know not only how to stop it, but also check if the items are in fact certified goods. Ask them.

Person with a serious fit of anger. "WHY YOU TELL EVERYONE HOW TO HACK MY DOMAIN?!"

Now now, calm down. Like I said, almost any scripter worth their salt already knew this. When it comes to manipulating objects, like say a watch or floating pet, we edit entities all the time. In fact, unless otherwise updated, objects that are grabbed are really executing an edit command to parent the entity to themselves! This is why if you ever grabbed a material, you'd find it started to effect you.

Not to mention, compared to avatar theft, preventing people from editing in your domain is completely doable, but is also not malicious at all! It's built into the system itself as a core feature, and as more things become entity based (RIP Overlays), domain owners will just have to remember to lock things down or expect it to turn into a rocket that even Jebediah Kerman would find impressive.

